          <h2>Introduction to Red Giant Stars</h2>
          <p>Red giant stars are among the most dramatic examples of stellar evolution. These bloated, luminous stars represent what happens when a <a href="/atlas/stars/main-sequence/">main sequence</a> star exhausts the hydrogen fuel in its core. Unable to sustain the fusion that kept it stable for billions of years, the star undergoes radical changes—its core contracts while its outer layers expand to enormous dimensions.</p>

          <p>The name "red giant" is descriptive: these stars are both red (having cool surface temperatures of 3,000-5,000 K) and giant (having expanded to perhaps 10-100 times their main sequence radius). Despite their cool surfaces, red giants are highly luminous because their vast surface area more than compensates for their lower temperature per unit area.</p>

          <p>Some of the most familiar stars in the night sky are red giants. Arcturus, the fourth brightest star visible from Earth, is a red giant about 25 times the Sun's radius. Aldebaran, the "eye" of Taurus the Bull, is another prominent red giant. These stars give us a preview of the Sun's own fate billions of years from now.</p>
        </section>

